    {
      "id": 137692,
      "category": "researcher",
      "content": "Glassdoor sent me an email asking me to upload my resume on Job portal. This email provided a direct link to the upload screen. Interestingly, the URL had a query string parameter for `Job Alert ID`. I just intercepted the response to `GET` request for this URL and noticed the email address associated with that Job Alert ID was present in the response even though I was unauthenticated. Now this ID is no big deal as it is just a 10 digit number auto created (sequentially) when a user creates a job alert or completes initial survey after sign up. \n\nAll the attacker would have needed to do was to create a job alert and capture the alert id and  send requests to vulnerable endpoint by decrementing the JobAlert ID to steal email addresses. \n\nBy  exploiting this vulnerability, an attacker (even without authentication) could have extracted **millions of email addresses** of Glassdoor users.\n\n\nThanks to Glassdoor team for their super quick response in addressing this.",
